  "prompt": "What is the difference between gypsum and marble?",
  "response": "Gypsum and marble are both minerals used in construction and decorative applications, but they have several key differences:\n\n1. Composition:\n- Gypsum: Calcium sulfate dihydrate (CaSO4\u00b72H2O)\n- Marble: Metamorphosed calcium carbonate (CaCO3)\n\n2. Formation:\n- Gypsum: Sedimentary rock formed by evaporation of mineral-rich water\n- Marble: Metamorphic rock created by transformation of limestone under heat and pressure\n\n3. Hardness:\n- Gypsum: Soft (Mohs hardness of 2)\n- Marble: Relatively harder (Mohs hardness of 3-4)\n\n4. Appearance:\n- Gypsum: Usually white or colorless, can be translucent\n- Marble: Often comes in various colors with veined patterns\n\n5. Uses:\n- Gypsum: Drywall, plaster, cement, agricultural applications\n- Marble: Sculpture, architecture, decorative surfaces, countertops\n\n6. Water solubility:\n- Gypsum: Slightly soluble in water\n- Marble: Relatively insoluble in water\n\nThese differences make each material suitable for different applications in construction and design.",
